Detail of Peter Dean’s 1972 portrait of Boris Lurie. 

Boris Lurie (July 18, 1924 – January 7, 2008) was an American artist and writer. He co-founded the NO!Art movement which calls for socially and politically involved art that would resist and combat the forces of the market. His controversial work, often related to the Holocaust, has frequently irritated critics and curators.

I’m just such a huge fan of Dean’s use of color and texture to capture his subjects. 

This work, as well as an exceptional portrait of his friend Orellana, is available through @smythemckee and the link in bio.

Truly impossible to summarize our visit to Angkor Wat (and two other nearby temples) in Cambodia today. 

This UNESCO world heritage site was constructed as a Hindu temple in the 12th c, but was quickly converted for Buddhist use. 

At the time there were nearly 1 million people living in the region, with about half dedicated to building this and other temples. The region of Angkor Wat was the same size as the city of London, which only had about 35,000 residents at the time. 

Using elephants, several types of stone were brought from the quarry 30 miles away. 

In addition to the structure, the wall carvings that encircle the entire temple tel fascinating stories of daily life, great battles, and legends of the gods. 

Also, the monkeys are the cutest things ever. 

1000% worth a visit if you are in this beautiful part of the world. 

Have you been? What did you think?

A master of action painting, Edvins Strautmanis would lay his canvases on the floor of his studio and use various utensils like brooms and homemade brushes to thrust the pigment across the surface, creating bold, active movement. 

This work, from later in his career is a masterwork of his signature style. The composition is particularly strong, as concentric frames draw the eye to the splash of saturated blue paint at the center. 

Additional work by the artist is available at the link in bio. 

The work comes directly from the estate# of Alan Stone, the legendary art dealer who passed in 2004. 

Shipping in the continental US is complimentary.

Where do you turn when you’re burned out?

Is the market done with Hans Hofmann, or is he still undervalued? 

Born in 1880 (!), Hofmann was hugely influential in European and American modern art. He taught many of the greats including Frankenthaler, Nevelson, and Krasner. 

His career spanned 60 years and he was incredibly prolific. In a modern market where collectors need to be able to instantly identify an artist, does this longevity hurt him?

I’m all in on Hofmann, but I can see why artists with more distinct styles and less diverse output have had better market value. Thoughts?

Have you been to an art fair before? If not, why? Do you find them intimidating?

Art fairs are actually one of the best ways to see a huge variety of modern and contemporary art, all in one place with a low barrier to entry. 

One day-pass to an art fair will allow you to experience art from 100-200 top dealers. Better yet, they send friendly sales staff who are happy to talk to you about the art and tell you the prices. No snobby gallery girls guarding the information here!

I’m looking forward to the Armory Show, Paris +, and Art Basel Miami Beach this fall.

I am SO excited about @anthamlyn’s first solo show in Spain! 

Opening this Friday at @galeriayustoginer, Hamlyn narrates an innocent but persuasive "he loves me - he loves me not" of folklore and popular beliefs.

Sam Gilliam’s late work @pacegallery 

I’ll always be a fan, but these works are  missing some of the grit and nuance of his work from the 1970’s. When you compare these pieces (likely made by studio assistants) to Gilliam’s all-over works like Firefly Blacktop (1970 @highmuseumofart), there’s a real contrast in the depth and character. Looking at the work from 1970 (slide 3), you see the energy just seeping out from under the top layers of black pigment. 

The present works feel like someone wrote a description of Gilliam’s style and tried to recreate it in a lab. It’s just missing something. 

What do you think?

👀 You’re gonna want to see this 👀

Tetsuya Ishida (b. 1973 d. 2005) was a member of Japan's "Lost Generation" (1991 - 2001), Ishida was a firsthand witness to the country's economic decline that began in the 1990s and extended into the 2000s. Subsequently, the angst that characterized his age group affected his perceptions of Japan's near-future where he viewed it as a bleak, urbanized atmosphere dominated by technocratic occupations that drain life from citizens. 

Ishida’s estate is now represented by @gagosian and have an eerie relevance to life today.

1) Lots of Henry Taylor (no surprise, as he has a major show at the Whitney)

7) Who is buying all the late Bernard Buffet? There’s far too much of it on offer.
